==Dutch==
===Etymology===
From {{etyl|dum|nl}} {{term|sien|lang=dum}}, from {{etyl|odt|nl}} {{term|sian|lang=odt}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|nl}} {{m|gem-pro|*sehwaną}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|nl}} {{m|ine-pro|*sekʷ-||to see, notice}}. Cognate with Low German {{term|sehn|lang=nds}}, West Frisian {{term|sjen|lang=fy}}, German {{term|sehen|lang=de}}, English {{term|see|lang=en}}, Danish and Swedish {{term|se|lang=sv}}, Icelandic {{term|sjá|lang=is}}, Gothic {{term|𐍃𐌰𐌹𐍈𐌰𐌽|tr=saiƕan|lang=got}}.

''zien'' was originally a class 5 strong verb. There was originally an 'h' sound in ''zien'', which was lost from the infinitive and present tense forms through [[syncope]] in Old Dutch. However, the 'h' sound alternated with a 'g' in the past tense through [[w:Grammatischer Wechsel|Grammatischer Wechsel]], and this remained.

